Some facts about PCOS:
 
-PCOS affects about 1 in 10 women of childbearing age

-Its symptoms can begin shortly after puberty, but can also develop during later teen years & during adulthood

-PCOS can also come about after stopping hormonal birth control like the pill

-There are 5 different types of PCOS, each with their own ‘driver’ of the condition. These are excess androgens, insulin resistance, post-pill hormonal imbalance, inflammation & adrenal impairment

-Having cysts on your ovaries doesn’t have much to do with PCOS at all, in fact most healthy women of childbearing age have multiple cysts on their ovaries called follicles

-PCOS can be managed well once you’ve figured out the main ‘driver’
 
Do you have an irregular menstrual cycle or has your period completely disappeared? Have you noticed excess growth of facial and body hair, yet the hair on your scalp is thinning? Perhaps you’re suffering from jawline acne, your skin is getting oiler or you’re gaining weight unexplainably? These are just some of the symptoms of PCOS and will vary from woman to woman.
 
