Women with PCOS produce higher-than-normal amounts of male hormones. This hormone imbalance causes them to skip menstrual periods and makes it harder for them to get pregnant.
PCOS also causes hair growth on the face and body, and baldness. And it can contribute to long-term health problems like diabetes and heart disease.
Up to 70 percent of women with PCOS have insulin resistance, meaning that their cells can’t use insulin properly 
Insulin is a hormone the pancreas produces to help the body use sugar from foods for energy.
When cells can’t use insulin properly, the body’s demand for insulin increases. The pancreas makes more insulin to compensate. Extra insulin triggers the ovaries to produce more male hormones.
#Obesity is a major cause of insulin resistance. Both obesity and insulin resistance can increase your risk for type 2 diabetes
How #PCOS affects your body
Having higher-than-normal androgen levels can affect your fertility and other aspects of your #health.
Infertility
To get pregnant, you have to ovulate. Women who don’t ovulate regularly don’t release as many eggs to be fertilized. PCOS is one of the leading causes of infertility in women 
Metabolic syndrome
Up to 80 percent of women with PCOS are overweight or obese
 Both obesity and PCOS increase your risk for high blood sugar, high blood pressure, low HDL (“good”) cholesterol, and high LDL (“bad”) cholesterol.
Together, these factors are called metabolic syndrome, and they increase the risk for heart disease, #diabetes, and stroke.
Sleep apnea
This condition causes repeated pauses in breathing during the night, which interrupt sleep.
Sleep apnea is more common in women who are overweight — especially if they also have PCOS. The risk for #sleep apnea is 5 to 10 times higher in obese women with PCOS than in those without PCOS 
Endometrial cancer
During ovulation, the uterine lining sheds. If you don’t ovulate every month, the lining can build up.
A thickened uterine lining can #increase your risk for endometrial cancer
#Depression
Both hormonal changes and symptoms like unwanted #hair growth";}i:186;a:1:{s:14:"comments_count";i:1;}i:187;a:1:{s:11:"likes_count";i:7;}i:188;a:1:{s:4:"link";s:39:"https://www.instagram.com/p/CEvSs2dgQ6V";}i:189;a:1:{s:5:"image";s:237:"https://scontent-sin6-2.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.2885-15/e35/118873479_630766497850361_592261160473834665_n.jpg?_nc_ht=scontent-sin6-2.cdninstagram.com&_nc_cat=105&_nc_ohc=vfQ4v_z-AUAAX_jv5HC&oh=69f304bcbc570b898bd4798e20089ea1&oe=5F7C68E2";}i:190;a:1:{s:4:"type";s:7:"sidecar";}i:191;a:1:{s:8:"owner_id";i:520788366;}i:192;a:1:{s:14:"owner_username";s:0:"";}i:193;a:1:{s:14:"owner_fullname";s:0:"";}i:194;a:1:{s:9:"owner_pic";s:0:"";}i:195;a:1:{s:2:"id";s:19:"2391211809929882808";}i:196;a:1:{s:10:"short_code";s:11:"CEvSnjRluy4";}i:197;a:1:{s:12:"created_time";i:1599274682;}i:198;a:1:{s:7:"caption";s:2190:"5 WEEKS POST HYSTERECTOMY!!! 

I never had a period until I was almost 16 and even then, there was nothing normal about what I felt.

More than 10 years ago - I found out I had PCOS. 

3 years ago - I had to stop jogging, running, walking, and doing much of anything physically because it all caused extreme pain in my uterus and the pain would radiate. 

It got so bad, I needed to see a doc (I thought it was normal until about 3 years ago). Birth control for a year - made it worse.

I has an excision surgery in Nov 2019 and she told me there wasn't much. 

I had a hysterectomy 5 weeks ago and he said he removed a lot of endo, esp around my right ovary and showed me my PCOS. 

Before my hysterectomy,  I experienced pain every. single. day.  My uterus was the primary source of my pain.  I could feel it.  It felt like my uterus was constantly attacking my body.  My hips hurt soooo freaking bad, there were days I literally couldn't pick up my right leg to walk to the restroom.  It hurt down into my legs so bad.  Down to my knees.  My back.  The pain caused so much fatigue and crying.  I ended up on an anti depressant (started taking it a year ago) (so I could stop crying from all the pain). The pain was so constant.... so freaking constant... bowl issues.  There was never enough heat on my back and on my lower abdomen.  It was never hot enough!!!! I could have burn marks and it still was not hot enough.. 

These past 5 weeks.... since my hysterectomy... AMAZING (not perfect, but so much freaking better)!! I will take surgical pain every day for the rest of my life if that means I dont have to experience that endo/pcos again.  I can't begin to describe it.  I know a hysterectomy isn't a cure... but it worked for me, my emotions, and my body.

I know I'm still healing and I promise I'm listening to my body!! I can not begin to tell you all the ways I feel so much better!!! I even have been taking short (leisurely) walks!!

